04774nam a22007455i 9781400837564DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20102006nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008375647 a10.1515/97814008375642doi  a(DE-B1597)453582  a(OCoLC)979749690  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aGT2112 7aSOC0480002bisacsh04a391.4/309441 aBowen, John R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhy the French Don't Like Headscarves :bIslam, the State, and Public Space /cJohn R. Bowen.  aCourse Book 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2010] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b6 halftones.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tONE. Introduction -- tPart 1. State and Religion in the Long Run -- tTWO. Remembering Laïcité -- tTHREE. Regulating Islam -- tPart 2. Publicity and Politics, 1989–2005 -- tFOUR. Scarves and Schools -- tFIVE. Moving toward a Law -- tSIX. Repercussions -- tPart 3. Philosophy, Media, Anxiety -- tSEVEN. Communalism -- tEIGHT. Islamism -- tNINE. Sexism -- tTEN. Conclusions -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe French government's 2004 decision to ban Islamic headscarves and other religious signs from public schools puzzled many observers, both because it seemed to infringe needlessly on religious freedom, and because it was hailed by many in France as an answer to a surprisingly wide range of social ills, from violence against females in poor suburbs to anti-Semitism. Why the French Don't Like Headscarves explains why headscarves on schoolgirls caused such a furor, and why the furor yielded this law. Making sense of the dramatic debate from his perspective as an American anthropologist in France at the time, John Bowen writes about everyday life and public events while also presenting interviews with officials and intellectuals, and analyzing French television programs and other media. Bowen argues that the focus on headscarves came from a century-old sensitivity to the public presence of religion in schools, feared links between public expressions of Islamic identity and radical Islam, and a media-driven frenzy that built support for a headscarf ban during 2003-2004. Although the defense of laïcité (secularity) was cited as the law's major justification, politicians, intellectuals, and the media linked the scarves to more concrete social anxieties--about "communalism," political Islam, and violence toward women. Written in engaging, jargon-free prose, Why the French Don't Like Headscarves is the first comprehensive and objective analysis of this subject, in any language, and it speaks to tensions between assimilation and diversity that extend well beyond France's borders.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aClothing and dressxPolitical aspectszFrance. 0aClothing and dressxReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aHijab (Islamic clothing)zFrance. 0aIslam and secularismzFrance. 0aMuslim womenxClothingzFrance. 0aVeilsxSocial aspectszFrance. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Islamic Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044250240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140083756440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400837564423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400837564.jpg  a978-3-11-044250-2  Princeton University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME